The main proposals in the Roadmap as depicted in Table ES-11 are as follows:
* in 2025, the target of 35% renewable energy in the electricity mix will be achieved with an additional of 396 GWh of renewable energy over the period 2020-2025.
* in 2030, the target of 40% can be achieved, provided that the appropriate wave energy technology is commercialized and the cost of offshore wind goes down;
* the contribution of solar energy in the electricity mix is expected to increase from 1.7% in 2018 to 10.2% in 2025 and 13.7% in 2030;
* onshore wind is forecast to increase from 0.4% in 2018 to 2.3% in 2030;
* biomass energy using bagasse and cane trash is expected to increase from 312 GWh in 2018 to 508 GWh in 2025 and 532 GWh in 2030. In terms of percentage share in the mix, it would be around 14-15% over the period 2025-2030.
* hydropower will not evolve significantly, as most of hydro power resources are already being exploited;
* offshore wind is not expected to be developed until 2030, when the technology advances further and prices become competitive. It can contribute to about 2.4% in 2030; and
* wave energy is expected to come into play by horizon 2030, if the technology becomes mature and commercially viable.

In addition, the following fiscal incentives have been put in place:
* an annual allowance of 50% on capital expenditure incurred on renewable energy technology equipment as from Financial Year 2015/16;
* any household investing in its own solar energy unit is allowed to deduct from its taxable income the total amount invested in such a unit, including photovoltaic kits and battery for storage of electricity, as from Financial Year 2015/16;
* photovoltaic system including photovoltaic generators, photovoltaic panels, photovoltaic batteries and photovoltaic inverters are VAT zero rated as from Financial Year 2016/17;
* exempt income in terms of interest derived by individuals and companies from debentures or bonds issued by a company to finance renewable energy projects as from Financial Year 2017/18; and
* additional remuneration from bagasse of Rs 1,250 per ton of sugar, bringing the revenue accruing from bagasse to Rs 2,500 for small planters and Rs 1,700 for other planters for crop season 2018.

Government has announced new measures in the Budget 2019/2020 to facilitate greater private investment in renewable energy. These measures include:
* the threshold of 30% of electricity consumption for sizing a PV unit is no longer required;
* the monthly fee for supplying electricity from solar energy sources to the national grid has been waived;
* a new scheme for the installation of solar PV systems for religious bodies will be implemented by the CEB. Part of the electricity consumption of these bodies will be free of charge under this scheme;
* new Renewable Energy Generation Schemes will be set up to encourage smart cities, small and medium scale power producers and public sector entities to generate electricity from solar PV; and
* a solar farm will be set up in the vicinity of the airport with a view to being more environmental friendly and allowing the new airport city to be fully autonomous and run by green energy.

There are four main types of devices being developed to convert ocean current energy:
* Horizontal Axis Turbines: Operates in the same way as a wind turbine, which converts the kinetic energy from the moving water using a turbine that looks similar to a wind turbine;
* Ducted Horizontal Axis Turbines: Similar to the horizontal axis turbine, except the turbine is housed inside a duct. This helps to concentrate the current flow through the turbine and may provide a better capacity factor;
* Vertical Axis Turbines: Operates in the same way as a vertical axis wind turbine and sits perpendicular to the ocean current flow; and
* Oscillating Hydrofoils: Utilises an oscillating hydrofoil system to extract energy from moving water. The hydrofoil can be similar to a shark fin or wing that oscillates or flaps in the ocean current flow to capture the kinetic energy.

